There are many people use a `script` tag link to a vue production build. There is no way to prevent a user from assigning `undefined` to an event handler in this situation. However, an `Error` will be thrown after a re-render if an event handler is undefined initially. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9816225/58849717-04908880-86be-11e9-9ade-81bf892ee7f2.png)

This pr fix the bug and bring us a more concise way to write conditional event binding.

**before:**
```js
{
  render(h) {
    return h('input', {
      on: this.ok
        ? {
            click: this.onClick,
          }
        : {},
    });
  }
}
```

**after:**
```js
{
  render(h) {
    return h('input', {
      on: {
        click: this.ok && this.onClick,
      },
    });
  }
}
```

